## Introduction üëã
```@raw html
<div class="markdown">
<p>In this tutorial, we'll cover the basics of using the PlantModules package. Here's a brief overview:</p><ul><li><p>Toy problem: when to water your pepper seedlings</p></li><li><p>Creating a modular plant model</p><ul><li><p>Defining structural and functional plant modules</p></li><li><p>Specifying model parameters</p></li><li><p>Describing how the modules interact</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Running the model</p></li><li><p>Answering the toy question</p></li></ul></div>


<div class="markdown"><h3>Toy problem description</h3><p>There is no fun in modeling without purpose, which is why we'll introduce the package with a simple problem.</p><p>Our recently sprouted pepper seedlings are growing on the windowsill indoors. We just watered them, and we'd like to know how the water content of the soil changes through time so we can water them again at the optimal moment: the soil should have dried adequately to promote root growth without putting the seedlings under too much drought stress.</p><p><img alt="plantfigu" src="https://www.almanac.com/sites/default/files/users/The%20Editors/pepper-seedlings_full_width.jpg"/></p></div>
```

## Modeling with PlantModules
```@raw html
<div class="markdown">
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p>As the name suggests, one of the most important goals of PlantModules is to enable the user to easily model plant growth in a <em>modular</em> manner. In order to achieve this, we will define our plant in function of a few sets of similarly behaving parts or "modules" for short. Parts of the same module can be similar on the structural - and on the functional level.</p><p>On the structural level, some examples are:</p><ul><li><p>An oak tree can be considered a repeating module in a forest.</p></li><li><p>A branch can be considered a repeating module in a tree.</p></li><li><p>A collenchyma cell can be considered a repeating module in a branch.</p></li></ul><p>On the functional level, on the other hand:</p><ul><li><p>Most structural modules of a tree (branches, leaves, root segments, etc.) contain water which will flow between them as dictated by hydraulic laws, which plays an important role in plant growth. All these structural modules share this same functional module. </p></li><li><p>One or more of the plant's structural modules will assimilate carbon through photosynthesis, while the others do not. On the cellular level, only cells containing chloroplasts should share this functional module.</p></li></ul><p>As such, the workflow to create a model in PlantModules boils down to defining these modules and how they interact. Let's jump right in!</p></div>


```
## The structure
```@raw html
<div class="markdown">
</div>


<div class="markdown"><h3>The plant</h3><p>The first step in modeling our plant's growth is defining its structure. For the first tutorial, we'll consider a very simple example: an organ-scale plant model of a plant with two leaves, a stem and a root system.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>PlantModules uses <strong>graphs</strong> to define the relationships between modules. As such, structural modules need to be implemented as graph nodes of some sort. We'll be using the graph implementation from <a href="https://virtualplantlab.com/stable/manual/Graphs/">the PlantGraphs</a> package for this tutorial, though <a href="nothinghere">any graph implementation can be used</a>.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>Then we can define the structural modules of our plant. For our example, we will define three structural modules on the organ scale of the plant.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>mutable struct Root &lt;: Node end</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>mutable struct Stem &lt;: Node end</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>mutable struct Leaf &lt;: Node
    D::Vector
end</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><p>And then define the plant structure using a graph</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>plant_graph = Root() + Stem() + (Leaf([2]), Leaf([2.5])); # Leaves are chosen to be  modelled as spheres and are here given radii of 2 and 2.5 cms</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><p>Individual graph nodes can contain parameter values and initial values to allow differences between nodes of the same type. Here, we'll give the leaves a size field <code>D</code> so we can start off one of them larger than the other. We'll see more on parameter - and initial values later.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><h3>The environment</h3><p>Plants need an environment to grow in. For most plants, the most basic environmental compartments that need defining are the soil, from which the plant gets water and nutrients, and the air, with which the plant exchanges gasses and to which it loses water. </p><p>For more intricate models one may for example also want to take into account the sun as well as possible sources of shadow or divide the soil into multiple compartments, but we will stick to the basics for now.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>struct Soil &lt;: Node end</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>struct Air &lt;: Node end</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><p>We also need to define the connections between these environmental modules and the plant. Sadly, connecting both leaf nodes to the air would introduce a cycle into our graph, which is something many plant-focused graph implementations do not support.</p><p>To overcome this, PlantModules allows the user to input multiple graphs and then specify how to connect them:</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>soil_graph = Soil();</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>air_graph = Air();</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>graphs = [plant_graph, soil_graph, air_graph];</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>intergraph_connections = [[1, 2] =&gt; (:Root, :Soil), [1, 3] =&gt; (:Leaf, :Air), [2, 3] =&gt; (:Soil, :Air)]; # Let's also add a connection between the soil and the air to simulate direct evaporation</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><p>The above syntax means: "connect all Root nodes from <code>graphs[1]</code> to all Soil nodes from <code>graphs[2]</code>", and so on. Note that the order matters! For example, <code>[1, 2] =&gt; (:Root, :Soil)</code> is not the same as <code>[2, 1] =&gt; (:Root, :Soil)</code>.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>struct_connections = PlantStructure(graphs, intergraph_connections);</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><p>The full structural connection information can then be acquired by putting them together in a vector.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><blockquote><p>For our tiny example plant, we only have one structural module that actually repeats, somewhat defeating the purpose of modelling in a modular manner: we may as well write this entire model out by hand! Rest assured, however, that the approach we're seeing here also works for larger plants, as we will see in the next tutorial.</p></blockquote></div>


```
## The function
```@raw html
<div class="markdown">
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p>Now that we have an idea of the plant's structural modules, we need to define some sort of functionality expressed by one or more of them. Some examples, such as only a select set of structural modules doing photosynthesis, have been mentioned before. In this tutorial, we'll mostly neglect carbon dynamics and instead focus on the plant's water dynamics.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><h3>Defining functional modules</h3></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>PlantModules defines functional modules as as sets of differential equations implemented in <a href="https://docs.sciml.ai/ModelingToolkit/stable/">ModelingToolkit</a>. There are five functional modules already provided by PlantModules:</p><ul><li><p><code>hydraulic_module</code>, which describes the hydraulics-driven growth of a compartment.</p></li><li><p><code>environmental_module</code>, which describes a compartment that is subject to hydraulic laws but does therefor not change in size.</p></li><li><p><code>constant_carbon_module</code>, which describes a compartment with a constant amount of carbon.</p></li><li><p><code>Œ®_soil_module</code>, which describes an empirical relationship between the total water potential and relative water content of soil.</p></li><li><p><code>Œ®_air_module</code>, which describes the relationship between the total water potential and water potential of air.</p></li></ul></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>The first module contains the most important functionality of the package, whereas the other four are mostly to allow for implementing a model that works out of the box. Users that want to create a realistic model are expected to implement some functional modules of their own in accordance with their own use for the package, as will be discussed next tutorial. For now, we will stick to the pre-implemented functional modules.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><h3>Defining parameter and initial values</h3></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>Next to the equations themselves, an important part in describing the plant's functional processes is defining the equations' parameter - and initial values. Since we'll restrict ourselves to hydraulic equations for this tutorial, these parameters and variables are the ones described in the section <a href="nothinghere">Theoretical overview</a>.</p><p>In PlantModules, parameter - and initial values are defined in a hierarchical manner, here listed in ascending priority:</p><blockquote><p><strong>Model-wide default values &lt; module-specific default values &lt; node-specific values</strong></p></blockquote><p>For our current example, this means that there is no point in specifying the initial values for the compartment dimensions <em>D</em> for our Leaf compartments in the module-specific default values or the model-wide default values, since we already defined these values in all of the Leaf nodes of the graph, which have the highest priority.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>Before we change any of the default parameter - and initial values, we can take a look at the defaults used by PlantModules:</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>PlantModules.default_values</code></pre>
<pre class="code-output documenter-example-output" id="var-hash134498">Dict{Symbol, Any} with 13 entries:
  :D        =&gt; [0.5, 5.0]
  :te_night =&gt; 0.1
  :W_r      =&gt; 0.8
  :K        =&gt; 500
  :W_max    =&gt; 1.0e6
  :M        =&gt; 0.0003
  :K_s      =&gt; 500
  :sunrise  =&gt; 8
  :Œì        =&gt; 0.3
  :T        =&gt; 298.15
  :sunset   =&gt; 20
  :Œ®        =&gt; -4.71892e-11
  :shape    =&gt; Cylinder{Vector{Float64}}([0.5, 0.5], [0.005, 0.005])</pre>


<div class="markdown"><p>Now imagine we have some information on our plant in question and it calls for different default values. These changes will be inputted as a Dictionary:</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>default_changes = Dict(:Œì =&gt; 0.4, :T =&gt; 293.15);</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><p>Next to changing functional values over the entire model, some of the information we have may require different default values specifically for certain structural modules. We can specify this as shown below.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>module_defaults = Dict(
    :Root =&gt; Dict(:shape =&gt; Cuboid([5.0, 10.0, 20.0], [0.7, 0.1, 0.05]), :D =&gt; [30, 3, 1], :M =&gt; 300e-6),
    :Stem =&gt; Dict(:D =&gt; [1.5, 10], :M =&gt; 400e-6),
    :Leaf =&gt; Dict(:shape =&gt; Sphere(3.0, 0.45), :M =&gt; 450e-6),
    :Soil =&gt; Dict(:W_max =&gt; 500.0, :K =&gt; 5),
    :Air =&gt; Dict(:W_r =&gt; 0.7, :K =&gt; 0.03)
);</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><p>As you can see, we changed the default <span class="tex">\(shape\)</span> between the root, stem and leaf modules, as well as their initial dimensions <span class="tex">\(D\)</span> and metabolite concentration <span class="tex">\(M\)</span>. For our soil module, we changed the maximum water content and temperature. For a detailed explanation of the parameters and initial values here, we again refer to the <a href="nothinghere">theoretical overview</a>.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><h3>The connections</h3><p>The next step is to define how nodes interact with eachother, which is again implemented as sets of ODEs. Defining a new functional connection module is discussed in the following tutorial. The main two pre-implemented modules are:</p><ul><li><p><code>const_hydraulic_connection</code>: The waterflow conductivity <code>K</code> is constant and must be set when defining the connection.</p></li><li><p><code>hydraulic_connection</code>: The waterflow conductivity <code>K</code> is variable is calculated based on the conductivities <code>K</code> of the two plant parts that are connected.</p></li></ul></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>connecting_modules = [
    (:Soil, :Root) =&gt; (hydraulic_connection, Dict()),
    (:Root, :Stem) =&gt; (hydraulic_connection, Dict()),
    (:Stem, :Leaf) =&gt; (hydraulic_connection, Dict()),
    (:Leaf, :Air) =&gt; (hydraulic_connection, Dict()),
    (:Soil, :Air) =&gt; (const_hydraulic_connection, Dict(:K =&gt; 0.01))
];</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><p>These connecting modules define the functional information of the graph edges. In this case: the flow of water between nodes based on some hydraulic conductivity parameter and a difference in water potentials.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>The functional connections are then defined as follows.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>func_connections = PlantFunctionality(; default_changes, module_defaults, connecting_modules);</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><blockquote><p>‚ö† In contrast to the nodes, PlantModules currently does not support edges of the same type (that is, between the same structural modules) to specify different parameter - or initial values in the graph definition.</p></blockquote></div>


<div class="markdown"><h3>Coupling functional and structural modules</h3></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>Our model needs to know which structural modules make use of which functional modules. As perhaps the simplest part of our modeling workflow, we can define this using a <code>Vector</code> of <code>Pairs</code>.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>module_coupling = Dict(
    :Root =&gt; [hydraulic_module, constant_carbon_module, K_module],
    :Stem =&gt; [hydraulic_module, constant_carbon_module, K_module],
    :Leaf =&gt; [hydraulic_module, constant_carbon_module, K_module],
    :Soil =&gt; [environmental_module, Œ®_soil_module, constant_K_module],
    :Air =&gt; [environmental_module, Œ®_air_module, constant_K_module]
);</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><h3>Bringing it all together</h3></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>Now that we have all parts of our model defined, all that's left to do is putting it together. For this we use the main workhorse of PlantModules: <code>generate_system</code>.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>system = generate_system(struct_connections, func_connections, module_coupling);</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><p>This function will generate the <code>ODESystem</code> describing the model. It is possible to fine-tune the model even further at this stage as described in the <a href="nothinghere">Customizing the model</a> section of the docs, thought this should generally not be required.</p></div>


```
## Running the model üèÉ‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è
```@raw html
<div class="markdown">
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p>The rest of the modeling workflow is mostly taken care of by ModelingToolkit.jl and DifferentialEquations.jl, with some syntactic sugar added by PlantModules. For users that are unfamiliar with the package, it is recommended to take a brief look at <a href="https://docs.sciml.ai/ModelingToolkit/stable/">the ModelingToolkit docs</a> before proceeding.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>time_span = (0, 7*24.0); # We'll simulate our problem for a timespan of one week</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>sys_simpl = structural_simplify(system);</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>prob = ODEProblem(sys_simpl, [], time_span, warn_initialize_determined = false);</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>sol = solve(prob);</code></pre>



```
## Answering the toy problem
```@raw html
<div class="markdown">
<p>Finding the answer to our toy problem now comes down to plotting out the soil water content and visually inspecting when it gets too low:</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>plotgraph(sol, graphs[1:2], varname = :W)</code></pre>
<img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64,"/>


<div class="markdown"><p>We see the plant is readily taking up the soil's water until around 100h, at which point the soil water content remains about constant. Taking a look at the water potentials, we see this is because the soil water potential takes a dive when it gets this dry:</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>plotgraph(sol, graphs[1:2], varname = :Œ®)</code></pre>
<img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64,"/>


<div class="markdown"><p>And so we may conclude that we should water the plant again shortly after the 100h point if we don't want it to experience too much drought stress.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>The plant water dynamics in this tutorials were an oversimplification making these results are very iffy at best. Next tutorial we'll see how we can create our own functional processes to make the model more realistic.</p></div>
```
